post_text:
Numbers are going up, but Pontotoc county stays YELLOW. Please do all you can to help our school stay open!
*Check temperatures before the kids leave home each morning.
*If someone in the household is being tested for Covid, students need to stay home until results come in.
*The biggest risk of exposure at school is the bus route, you may want to transport your own children if you have that ability.
*Thank you for all you do to help us protect the pack!

post_text:
Vanoss Families---

As you know, Vanoss High School has now had three positive cases of Covid-19. In order to keep our students as safe as possible, we have decided to keep our High School closed through the following dates:
• Students who were quarantined Friday, August 28th and all students who were never quarantined may return Monday, September 14th.
• Students who were quarantined on Wednesday, Sept. 2nd (yesterday) may return Tuesday, Sept 15th.

Please remember that this affects our High School only. The Elementary and Middle Schools have had no cases of the virus and will continue in-person class as usual.

As we all know, everything involving this virus could change daily. It is our goal to continue to keep you informed as quickly as possible should anything occur. Please continue to monitor our school website and Facebook page for updates.

As always, thank you for your continued support. Even in these times, it's still a Great Day to Be A Wolf!

Oklahoma Hall of Fame at the Gaylord-Pickens Museum
August 22 at 11:14 AM ·

Attention all Oklahoma high school seniors and their parents, teachers and administrators — the Oklahoma Hall of Fame Scholarship application process officially closes in less than one month! Every year, we award one Oklahoma high school senior a $6,000 scholarship, which is based on the student's leadership roles, civic/community involvement, academic achievement and knowledge of our great state.

Students MUST commit to attending an Oklahoma college or university to be considered. Last year's recipient, Madison Stephens from Weatherford High School, was selected out of 95 applicants from 69 high schools in 40 counties across the state! 😲

Click here for more info and to download the nomination form: oklahomahof.com/scholarships

post_text: Vanoss English teacher Roy Deering!
shared_text:
The RoadRunner Press
July 31 at 3:52 PM ·

We're so proud to announce that Roy Deering's newest book THE DAY OLD FAITHFUL STOPPED—A YELLOWSTONE NATIONAL PARK MYSTERY has won the 2020 IPPY Silver Medal for juvenile fiction. The awards have been awarded annually for 24 years since 1996.

The book launches Deering's new NATIONAL PARK MYSTERY SERIES, and includes not one but 2 mysteries set in the wilds of America's first national park. Thomas Hilley did the WPA-poster-inspired cover.

That's part of the beauty of books: you may not feel safe to travel but as long as you have a good book, you can travel without ever leaving your house.

A big thank you to Beverly Deering for providing the photo.

July 25, 2020

Out of an abundance of being overly cautious we want to inform you about a positive case of COVID-19 in our school. The Pontotoc County Health Department has been contacted and does not feel this person was contagious during enrollment nor has this person been on campus since that time.

The safety and well-being of students and employees is our top priority. This particular situation does not require us to notify anyone. Again, we are doing this out of an abundance of caution and will continue to follow the CDC guidelines.

Due to confidentiality no other information can be given out at this time. Please refer to the CDC website for more information about COVID-19 @ www.cdc.gov.

Sincerely,

Marjana Tharp
Superintendent
Vanoss Public Schools

Vanoss Public Schools
July 17 at 10:21 AM ·

ENROLLMENT INFORMATION

Vanoss in-person student enrollment will be this coming Tuesday, July 21st, from 10am to 7pm. If you would like to fill out your paperwork early, we have packets available just inside the front door of the school from 7am to 4pm Monday. You can also print all forms from the school website.

In order to keep our students as safe as possible, we will have different grade levels spread out around the school during enrollment, and temperatures will be taken of all children and adults before we enter the school. Masks are highly recommended but not required.

If your students are in grades PK-8 and you would like to just drop off your packet and not enter the building, we will have a box by the front flagpole for that purpose.

If you have questions, please comment on this thread and we will try to answer them as we can.

In order to keep our students as safe as possible, we will have different grade levels spread out around the school during enrollment, and temperatures will be taken of all children and adults before we enter the school. Masks are highly recommended but not required.

If your students are in grades PK-8 and you would like to just drop off your packet and not enter the building, we will have a box by the front flagpole for that purpose.

If you have questions, please comment on this thread and we will try to answer them as we can.

The Chickasaw Nation
July 3 at 6:06 PM ·

The Chickasaw Nation is accepting applications for the Summer EBT for Children program. This federally funded program is available to both Native and non-Native students in more than 170 participating school districts.

Qualifying families receive approximately $30 of free food per child during summer months. Benefits are accessed through an EBT card, which works like a debit card that allows for the purchase of healthy food for the summer.

To qualify for this program, students must be enrolled in a participating school district in grades pre-K through grade 12 and receive free or reduced meals at school. Once approved, summer EBT cards are mailed to the address provided, along with a list of participating stores and a food card shopping list that helps identify approved items.

For more information, or to apply by phone, call Chickasaw Nation Summer EBT at (844) 256-3467.

A list of participating schools and an online application is available at Chickasaw.net/SummerEBT.

post_text:
Due June 15:

OETA Art Club Registration
Responding to the cancellation of traditional summer art camps across the state, OETA has partnered with the Oklahoma Arts Council and OSDE to launch the OETA Art Club, a virtual program that will provide arts instruction for students of all skill levels over the summer.
OETA Art Club will combine clips from OETA’s award-winning arts series, Gallery America, with discussion guides and activities for students in grades 6-12. Participants can expect a weekly art challenge using household materials based on a clip from Gallery America.
As a part of this 8-week program, students will:
• Receive exclusive links to weekly program materials
• Participate in a virtual Q&A with the show's host
• Upload their own unique artworks to OETA's social media
• Learn about Oklahoma's unique contributions to the arts and the Oklahomans who create the art
Students will need an internet connected device and basic art supplies. The program is free, but registration is required to participate. Registration is now open at OETA.tv/ArtClub and closes June 15

May 19 at 3:05 PM ·

FFA ALUMNI CAMP HAS BEEN CANCELLED.....🙁

Official email below.

Since 1973, FFA members have been provided an opportunity to grow as individuals, develop leadership skills, and fellowship with FFA members from across the state at the one and only Oklahoma FFA Alumni Leadership Camp. That’s why we have been hesitant to make the decision to cancel camp. Unfortunately, like many other things this summer, there will be no on-site Oklahoma FFA Alumni Leadership Camp in 2020.



The good news is that we are planning a virtual camp, July 27-29. It will feature our regulars, Bill Cordes, Kelly Barnes, and the newly elected State FFA Officer team. It will be free to FFA members and there is no limit on participation. We know that there is no way to 100% emulate what camp does in a virtual setting, but we are committed to providing top-notch leadership training for the agricultural youth of Oklahoma in these uncertain times, even if it is from a distance.

Keep that smile on your face and love in your heart and we will see you at the Virtual 2020 Oklahoma FFA Alumni Leadership Camp!

Vanoss Public Schools
May 14 at 2:02 PM ·

Vanoss schools will be having a "Grab 'n GO" locker clean out day this coming Monday, May 18th. We will be admitting students a few at a time in two shifts: from 9am to noon, and again from 5pm to 7pm.
Students should bring all items that they need to turn in to the school: library books, textbooks, calculators, electronic devices, ball uniforms, etc.
Students in grades 4-12 will be allowed to enter the building to remove their personal possessions from their lockers, and then exit the building.
For students in grades three and down, your possessions from the classroom will be bagged and available on the front lawn for you to pick up.
We will also have a copy of lunch balances available for those who would like to be caught up before enrollment for the next school year.
If you have any questions, please call the school office. Otherwise, see you Monday!

post_text: Vanoss High School is pleased to announce that we will be having an in-person senior graduation ceremony on Tuesday, June 2nd at 6:30pm in the Vanoss Activity Center. In keeping with social distancing guidelines from the state and federal government, there will be limit of four guests per graduate. While we realize that this is not the situation that any of us would have chosen, we are thankful to be able to offer a traditional graduation ceremony for this wonderful group of young people. More details will follow.

Oklahoma State Department of Education

Oklahoma Heritage Bank
April 8 at 4:02 PM ·

A student's senior year in high school is supposed to be an exciting time, with prom, graduation, and their senior trip on the horizon. Sadly for the class of 2020, this memorable time has been cut short due to the COVID-19 pandemic. Although there's not much any of us can do to ease their disappointment, we at OHB would like to do what we can to give your Senior the recognition they deserve.

Each Tuesday and Friday of the coming weeks, we will be featuring our area's super seniors on or social media pages! If you are the parent or grandparent of an AdaHigh School, Byng High School, RoffHigh School, Stratford Bulldogs, Latta High School, Vanoss High School, Allen High School of Allen, Oklahoma, or Stonewall High School senior, send us your graduate's name, high school, and their photo to kcupps@ohb.bank. Feel free to list any of their accomplishments, too! We are excited to give them the credit and attention they deserve!

Congratulations Class of 2020! We are proud of your accomplishments and resilience during this time!

post_text: And now for some good news-----We have been able to set the Vanoss school "Guest" WiFi up so that it is now accessible 24 hours a day, seven days a week. This means that any of our community members who do not have reliable internet access can simply come to the school and get on the schools high-speed WiFi while sitting in the parking lot. From the safety of your vehicle, you can download, upload, whatever you need to do. Since we still have to maintain a secure campus, there are two rules everyone must follow: You must park in front of the high school building main entrance (flag pole area). We can not allow anyone around the gym or other parts of the school. Secondly, all family members must remain in your vehicle. The school buildings and campus (including playgrounds) are still off-limits by order of the State. Otherwise, come and take advantage of the free WiFi for your school or family needs. It's a Great Day to be a Wolf!

Important news for our student athletes:

NCAA EC COVID-19 Response: Distance and E-Learning Programs
In response to questions regarding schools that have moved to distance or e-learning environments, the Eligibility Center will not require a separate review of distance or e-learning programs utilized by schools with NCAA-approved core courses that have moved to distance or e-learning environments for Spring/Summer 2020 terms due to school closures related to the COVID-19 situation.

Students are encouraged to complete their NCAA-approved core courses through the channels of instruction provided or recommended by their school, district or state department of education.

For information on COVID-19, please visit ncaa.org/COVID-19 and continue to monitor for more information from the Eligibility Center at on.ncaa.com/EC_COVID.

From the SDE:

How to Talk to Children About COVID-19

Why it’s important to discuss COVID-19 with children
Collectively, we are all involved in preventing the spread of COVID-19. Students, educators, families and communities must be aware of the facts involved in the coronavirus pandemic.

What should be included in the discussion?
Families and educators should remember to keep the conversation appropriate to the child’s developmental age. Share facts using age-appropriate terminology, actively listen to students’ concerns and answer their questions as best as you can. It’s okay to let them know if you are unsure of the answer.

How to communicate information about COVID-19 to children:
Stay calm and reassuring
Ask what they know or what they’ve heard
Keep children updated with facts
Be honest and available for discussions
Allow children to express their feelings
Validate their feelings
Limit media exposure

March 23 at 5:08 AM ·

Parents with school-age children at home, we need your help. All of our nursing homes are more-or-less on lockdown for the safety of some of our most vulnerable friends and neighbors. These folks, unfortunately, are losing contact with people they care deeply for. Jayci Jo Harris had a wonderful idea we want to take a step further. Have your kids write letters, draw pictures, take photos — have them create messages for our nursing home residents and send them to us at news@theadanews.com, or drop them through the night slot on our front door. We will scan them and publish them in the newspaper for our nursing home readers, so they know we’re all thinking of them.

Oklahoma State Department of Education
March 26 at 3:22 PM ·

Exciting news! 🎉 We have partnered with OETA to provide in-home learning opportunities for students. The goal is to bring parents, students and teachers together with content and curriculum to meet educational needs while schools are closed due to coronavirus.

Beginning Monday, March 30, OETA will be adjusting its daytime schedule to provide curriculum-based programming for students over the air on its broadcast channel, OETA WORLD. Programs will include PBS favorites like NOVA, Nature, American Experience and PBS KIDS programming.

Programming changes to OETA WORLD will take place Monday through Friday from 6 a.m. until 6 p.m. until the end of the school year.

Teachers and parents are encouraged to visit OETA.tv/LearningAtHome to view an updated program schedule, OETA’s statewide channel list, curriculum and activities.

post_text:
9:25 am OSSAA update:

UPDATE: 9:25 a.m.- Thursday, March 12--The OSSAA continues to actively monitor the public health concerns related to COVID-19. Our Staff has been in contact with the Oklahoma Department of Health this morning and based on the updates we have received, we will we proceed with all tournaments being played as scheduled. We do advise players, coaches, officials, contest workers and spectators to practice good hygiene by washing hands thoroughly and frequently; coughing and sneezing into kleenex and then immediately disposing of it are also recommended. If you have a fever or do not feel well, we ask that you not attend any games. Most games will be live-streamed on the NFHSNetwork.com. A link can be found on the homepage of OSSAA.com. Our Staff will continue to work with the State Health Department in monitoring the situation. The health and safety of all Oklahomans is a priority.

The Chickasaw Nation
March 11 at 8:46 AM ·

When schools close for spring break, many children lose access to daily meals and nutrition. The Chickasaw Nation is bridging this hunger gap by providing free meals at various locations across the Chickasaw Nation.

All children ages 1-18, both Native and non-Native, can receive meals the week of spring break, March 16-20, at these locations:

Ada ➡️ Nutrition Services, 10 a.m. to 5 p.m.; Chickasaw Nation WIC Clinic, 10 a.m. to 5 p.m.; Ada Public Library, 11:30 a.m. to 1 p.m.

Allen ➡️ Allen Public Library, noon to 1 p.m. and 3:30 to 4 p.m.

Ardmore ➡️ Chickasaw Nation Nutrition Services, 10 a.m. to 5 p.m.

Duncan ➡️ Chickasaw Nation Nutrition Services and the Chickasaw Nation WIC Clinic, 10 a.m. to 5 p.m.

Purcell ➡️ Chickasaw Nation Nutrition Services, 10 a.m. to 5 p.m.

Sulphur ➡️ Chickasaw Nation Area Office, 10 a.m. to 5 p.m.

For information and assistance, contact Chickasaw Nation Nutrition Services at (888) 436-7255.

#SpringBreak #NationalNutritionMonth

shared_text:
Bill Anoatubby is with Juanita Sutton-Green.
March 9 at 3:56 PM ·

The late Mary Jo Green dedicated nearly 40 years of service to the Chickasaw Nation and Chickasaw people. Her legacy includes helping establish our first senior citizens program and serving six terms in the tribal legislature. In 2017, she was recognized with the Chickasaw Nation’s highest honor, induction into the Chickasaw Hall of Fame.

A memorial scholarship honoring Mary Jo Green has been established through the Chickasaw Foundation. Because she had a passion for history and the law, the Mary Jo Green Memorial Scholarship will assist Chickasaw students studying these disciplines.

Students majoring in history, education or pre-law, or minoring in history with an emphasis on Chickasaw or Native American studies, can visit ChickasawFoundation.org or contact (580) 421-9030 to learn about scholarship opportunities.

shared_text:
Richard R. Barron is at Ada Cougar Activity Center.
March 6 at 10:06 PM · Ada, OK ·

With just seconds to go in overtime; one town on one side of the gym, another town on the other side of the gym. The ball hits nothing but net, and that team's town goes wild. The gym traps the din, filling all our ears with wild screams and yells. The buzzer sounds, and the game is over. One team and their town loses, one team and their town wins.

Covering this was my job tonight, and might be the most fun thing I do all year, year after year.
